<subSubSection pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="63.[151,1437,1160,1766]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,320,1276,1302]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[329,412,1276,1301]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[329,412,1276,1301]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Efferia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. is distinguished by the entirely black palpal setae, abundant black bristles of the face, blackish tomentum along the lateral margin of the face and below the epistomal margin, brownishyellow tomentum of the scutum and pleura, reddish femora and tibiae with only narrow apices black, and pale tomentum on the lateral margin of tergites 2–7. It is further distinguished by the short, wide terminalia and the oval, mostly brownish surface of the spermathecae (
<figureCitation box="[761,935,1431,1457]" captionStart="FIGURES 130–131" captionStartId="63.[151,269,1086,1110]" captionTargetBox="[167,1411,379,1027]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[152,1435,237,1073]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 130–131. Efferia sp. C. Female terminalia, lateral view: 130. Ovipositor; 131. Lateral spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455864/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Figs. 130–131</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="63.[151,1437,1160,1766]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
In 
<bibRefCitation box="[232,441,1469,1495]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" refId="ref38540" refString="Bromley, S. W. (1934) Asilidae. In: C. H. Curran, The Diptera of Karatabo, Bartica District, British Guiana, with descriptions new species from other British Guiana localities. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 66, 327 - 360." type="journal article">Bromley’s (1934)</bibRefCitation>
key, the Tobago-Trinidad species end in couplet 5 that includes 
<emphasis box="[1218,1436,1470,1495]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<taxonomicName box="[1218,1299,1470,1495]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Efferia</taxonomicName>
amazonica
</emphasis>
(Bromley) and 
<emphasis box="[330,416,1508,1533]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">E. titon</emphasis>
(Bromley). These are large (
<quantity box="[754,883,1508,1534]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.45" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="3.4" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="34.5" valueMax="35.0" valueMin="34.0">34–35 mm</quantity>
) flies with reddish femora and black markings, and uniformly brownish-gray tomentose abdomens. The femora of 
<emphasis box="[955,1116,1547,1572]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">E. amazonica</emphasis>
are mostly black ventrally whereas those of 
<emphasis box="[368,472,1586,1611]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">E. triton</emphasis>
have a wide, black, median spot dorsally. Contrastingly, the Tobago-Trinidad species is much smaller (
<quantity box="[452,584,1624,1650]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="13.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="11.0">11–15 mm</quantity>
), only the extreme apices of the femora are partly or completely black, and the abdominal tomentum is mostly gray with large brown spots dorsally. Also, the palpal setae of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">E. amazonica</emphasis>
are entirely whitish whereas they are black in this species. The palpal setae of 
<emphasis box="[1207,1305,1702,1727]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">E. triton</emphasis>
are mostly black, those basally whitish.
</paragraph>
